{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508025"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2706"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2706"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.05,0.45,0.02,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111128"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2706","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2706"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2706"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93252"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"297"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"4076"},{"type":"tags","id":"4210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3387"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17114"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18211"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39499"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41103"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45169"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45860"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111128","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111128"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 57-year-old postmenopausal woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of intermittent vaginal bleeding. She has no other genitourinary symptoms. Her medical history includes a left mastectomy for invasive ductal carcinoma eight years ago and type 2 diabetes. Her current medications are tamoxifen and metformin. There is no family history of malignancy. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 34 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E. Abdominal and pelvic examinations are normal. The self-collected cervical screening test 14 months ago was negative for human papillomavirus (HPV). \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Endometrial biopsy","Dilatation and curettage","Cervical co-test","CT abdomen","MRI pelvis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPostmenopausal bleeding can be a symptom of both endometrial and cervical cancer. While endometrial cancer is more common, cervical cancer must also be considered. The two important investigations that must be considered at this stage are the cervical co-test and an endometrial biopsy. This patient is in the general practitioner\u0027s room and endometrial biopsies (pipelle) are not routine procedures done in these circumstances. The patient will need a gynaecological review for this procedure. Whilst the patient is in the general practice clinic a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecervical co-test\u003C/strong\u003E can be performed. This helps in identifying cervical abnormalities that could be contributing to the bleeding. Although the patient had a negative HPV test 14 months ago from a self-collected sample, a co-test (which includes both HPV testing and cytology) is warranted in this situation. The co-test may detect abnormal endocervical cells or endometrial cells that could explain the bleeding. Cervical screening test is only for asymptomatic patients and HPV only is tested unless it is positive, then cytology is completed. Symptomatic patients with abnormal bleeding need a \u003Cstrong\u003Eco-test\u003C/strong\u003E which includes both \u003Cstrong\u003EHPV AND cytology\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eendometrial biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E (such as a pipelle) is an important step in the evaluation of postmenopausal bleeding for suspicion of ovarian cancer, but it is performed after initial assessments of cervical co-test and imaging. It is more invasive than a cervical co-test and is usually performed by a gynaecologist rather than a general practitioner. The cervical co-test is less invasive and can provide crucial information about cervical pathology that might be contributing to the bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDilatation and curettage (D\u0026amp;C)\u003C/strong\u003E is a more invasive procedure that provides a thorough sampling of the endometrium. While it may ultimately be necessary, it\u0027s not the most appropriate first step. D\u0026amp;C is typically performed by a gynaecologist after initial investigations have been completed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is not a first-line investigation for postmenopausal bleeding. While it can provide information about pelvic structures, it is less sensitive than transvaginal ultrasound for evaluating the endometrium and is associated with radiation exposure. CT is more commonly used in cancer staging rather than initial diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a first-line investigation for postmenopausal bleeding. It is more expensive and less readily available than ultrasound. MRI is typically reserved for cases where endometrial cancer has been diagnosed and staging is required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to note that this patient has several risk factors for endometrial cancer, including obesity (BMI 34 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E), type 2 diabetes, and tamoxifen use. These factors increase endogenous estrogen levels or directly stimulate endometrial proliferation, raising the risk of endometrial hyperplasia and cancer. The risk of endometrial cancer in tamoxifen users is approximately four times higher than in non-users.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPostmenopausal bleeding can be a symptom of both endometrial and cervical cancer. While endometrial cancer is more common, cervical cancer must also be considered, especially if there is a history of abnormal cervical screening results or symptoms suggestive of cervical pathology. The cervical co-test helps in identifying cervical abnormalities that could be contributing to the bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn reality, this patient would have a co-test performed and be referred for a semi-urgent transvaginal ultrasound, and then be referred to gyanecology irrespective of the co-test results for likely endometrial biopsy. The combination of her risk factors and postmenopausal bleeding warrants a thorough investigation to rule out malignancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pre-operative examination can give important clinical information.","Cervical co-testing is an appropriate first step in investigating postmenopausal bleeding, even with a recent negative HPV test.","Postmenopausal bleeding can be a symptom of both endometrial and cervical cancer, and so investigations need to be considered to rule out both of these conditions."],"references":["Piatek, S., Warzecha, D., Kisielewski, F., Szymusik, I., Panek, G. and Wielgos, M. (2019), Pipelle biopsy and dilatation and curettage in clinical practice: are factors affecting their effectiveness the same?. J. Obstet. Gynaecol. Res., 45: 645-651. doi:10.1111/jog.13882","Abdaal A, Mushtaq Y, Khasati L, et al. Post-menopausal bleeding - Is transvaginal ultrasound a useful first-line investigation in tamoxifen users?.\u00a0Post Reprod Health. 2018;24(2):72-78. doi:10.1177/2053369118755190","RCOG Green top Guideline No. 67 (Feb 2016). Management of endometrial Hyperplasia.\u00a0https://www.rcog.org.uk/globalassets/documents/guidelines/green-top-guidelines/gtg_67_endometrial_hyperplasia.pdf. Accessed September 1, 2020.\u00a0Abdaal A, Mushtaq Y, Khasati L, et al. Post-menopausal bleeding - Is transvaginal ultrasound a useful first-line investigation in tamoxifen users?.\u00a0Post Reprod Health. 2018;24(2):72-78. doi:10.1177/2053369118755190","Ryu K-J, Kim MS, Lee YJ, et al. Risk of Endometrial Polyps, Hyperplasia, Carcinoma, and Uterine Cancer After Tamoxifen Treatment in PremenopausalWomen With Breast Cancer. JAMA Network Open. 2022;5(11):e2243951.","Cancer Council Australia. Investigation of abnormal vaginal bleeding. Cancer Council Australia. 2022. Available from: https://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/cervical-cancer/cervical-cancer-screening/signs-and-symptoms/investigation-of-abnormal-vaginal-bleeding"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93252"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2706"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93252","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93252"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-09T10:40:31+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-22T16:40:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2706"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111128"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.co